LogFile.Subject: A3
LogFile.FinalText: Identifying a good coffee is a relatively simple task to tasters, but giving an exact grade to each sample is different. The taster enjoys the coffee based on skills acquired with experience. However, their verdicts are far from precise, which makes it difficult to evaluate coffee in larger scale. A report published on Fapesp online, however, presents a promising product developed by Brazilian researchers: the "electronic tongue", a device that can evaluate flavors much more precisely than the human tongue. Parts of the human tongue surface are sensory receptors called taste buds, which identify tastes. Scientists from Emprapa have projected a taste sensor capable of evaluating nuances of flavor and the presence of impurities in beverages with more precision than the human taste buds. The researches modeled the tasting sense and used microelectrodes coated with a thin layer of conductive polymers to obtain a specific electric response for each substance. Unlike the taster, the device always provides a precise numeric result when it identifies a flavor that is equivalent to another one previously recorded, even when there is a mixture or combination of flavors.
